<dl id="n36181c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36181c">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36181c"> 181(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Lifeboat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[On the Verge of the Abyss]</font> &ldquo;Let things alone,&rdquo; the laws of supply and demand, and all the rest of the excuses by which those who stand on firm ground salve their consciences when they leave their brother to sink, how do they look when we apply them to the actual loss of life at sea? Does &ldquo;Let things alone&rdquo; man the <mark>lifeboat</mark>? <small> William Booth, <a name="WBDE" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WBDE"><cite title="source">In Darkest England and the Way Out</cite></a> (1893) Part 1, Chapter 5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
